Essential Terminal Commands

Navigation & Files:
ls -la: List all files, including hidden ones, in detailed format.
cd <directory>: Change directory.
cd ..: Move up one folder level.
pwd: Print working directory.
mkdir <name>: Create a new directory.
touch <file>: Create a new file.
rm <file>: Remove a file.
rm -rf <dir>: Remove a directory and its contents (use with caution).

System & Information:
top / htop: View running processes.
df -h: Check disk space usage.
whoami: Display current user.
sudo <command>: Execute a command with root/administrator privileges.

Help & Search:
man <command>: Show the manual page for a command.
history: Show command history.
grep <pattern> <file>: Search for text inside a file.

Essential Keyboard Shortcuts:
Ctrl + C: Cancel/stop the current command.
Ctrl + L: Clear the screen.
Ctrl + R: Search through command history.
Tab: Auto-complete file names or commands.
!!: Repeat the last command.

ANSI Escape Codes (Styling):
These codes allow you to change text colors and cursor positions within scripts or command-line tools.
Format: \033[<parameters>m
Colors:
Reset: \033[0m
Red: \033[31m
Green: \033[32m
Yellow: \033[33m
Blue: \033[34m

Example (Bash): echo -e "\033[31mThis is red text\033[0m"

Common ASCII Codes (Control Characters)
BEL (Bell): \a or 0x07 - Makes a sound.
BS (Backspace): \b or 0x08 - Moves cursor back.
LF (Line Feed): \n or 0x0A - Newline.

Terminal Tricks
Open Finder (Mac): Type open . to open the current directory in Finder.
Copy/Paste in Windows (Git Bash): Ctrl + Insert to copy, Shift + Insert to paste.
Open Terminal in Folder (VS Code): Use Ctrl+Shift+Alt+ to open a new terminal panel.
